###STEP2: Import Mapping file (metadate file) 1.Check mapping file before import to R, R doesn’t seem to like sample name to start with number or contain “-” in sample name. If you get error in this step, you should check file name first.

2.First column of first row should not start with #, R will not read the first row that starts with #

metatable = file.path(knitr::opts_chunk$get("root.dir"),"Pilot_16S.mapping_file.txt")
meta = read.table(metatable,header=TRUE,row.names=1,sep=",",stringsAsFactors=FALSE)
rownames(meta) <- gsub('-','.',rownames(meta))

If need to keep or remove some samples

meta <- meta[which(meta$DemuxReads > min_read_count),]

###STEP5: Import OTU table

OTU table from Mojave 16S data is “MC2017FC.otu_table.txt”. MC-Mojave Crust-2017-FC-Fungi completed

otutable <- file.path(knitr::opts_chunk$get("root.dir"), "Pilot_16S.otu_table.txt")
otus <- read.table(otutable,header=T,sep="\t",row.names=1)
otumat <- as(as.matrix(otus), "matrix")
OTU = otu_table(otumat, taxa_are_rows = TRUE)

###STEP6: Import taxonomy table Taxonmy table generated from AMPtk need to be rearranged using following script.

“perl rdp_taxonmy2mat.pl<Input_taxonmy.txt>Output_taxonomy.txt”

rdp_taxonomy2mat.pl was created by Professor Jason E. Stajich

taxin = file.path(knitr::opts_chunk$get("root.dir"),"Pilot_16S.cluster.taxonomy.fix.txt")
taxmat <- read.table(taxin, header=T,sep="\t",row.names=1)
taxmat <- as(as.matrix(taxmat),"matrix")
TAX = tax_table(taxmat)

###STEP7: Import phylogenetic tree Phylogenetic tree can also be include for further phylogenetic analysis.

treefile = file.path(knitr::opts_chunk$get("root.dir"),"Pilot_16S.cluster.tree.phy")
tree = read.tree(treefile)

###STEP8: Construct Phyloseq object To construct phyloseq object, otu table, taxonomy table, and sampleData are required. Phylogenetic tree can be included, but it is not necessary for constructing phyloseq object. Construct Phyloseq object called “Physeq”

physeq = phyloseq(OTU,TAX,sampleData,tree)

Check phyloseq object This should indicate that your physeq is a “phyloseq-class experiment-level object”"

###STEP10: Plot read counts to check dataset Check read counts: any samples that have very low reads should be removed. Ref

readcount = data.table(as(sample_data(physeq.prune), "data.frame"),
                 TotalReads = sample_sums(physeq.prune), 
                 keep.rownames = TRUE)
setnames(readcount, "rn", "SampleID")
#For plotting, use command below.
#SeqDepth = ggplot(readcount, aes(TotalReads)) + geom_histogram() + ggtitle("Sequencing Depth")

TotalReads of all the samples can be in this table (select only SampleID and TotalReads columns). In order to check samples with low number of reads, “order()” can be used to sort “TotalReads” column. In this dataset, N55.Rhizo has very low number of reads, so will will filter this sample out using the next minimum number of reads.

readcount = readcount[order(readcount$TotalReads), c("SampleID", "TotalReads")]

physeq.prune.rarefy.ps.ord <- ordinate(physeq.prune.rarefy, "PCoA", "unifrac")

plot_ordination(physeq.prune.rarefy, physeq.prune.rarefy.ps.ord, type = "samples", color = "Extraction",shape="Treatment")  + ggtitle("Bacterial Beta Diversity (PCoA) by Owner")
## Warning: The shape palette can deal with a maximum of 6 discrete values because

taxcom_treatment = ggplot(data = psmelt(physeq.prune.rarefy), mapping = aes_string(x = "ExtractByTmt",
                                                                                   y = "Abundance", 
                                                                                   fill = "Phylum" )) + 
  geom_bar(stat="identity", position="fill") + 
  ggtitle("Bacteria from pilot study")+
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 90, hjust = 1)) +
  theme_bw() + theme(panel.grid.major = element_blank(), panel.grid.minor = element_blank(),
                     axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 90, vjust = 0.5, hjust=1)
                     ) +
  theme(plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5))

###Plot Alpha Diversity (Species richness)

physeq.prune.rarefy.plot.richness = plot_richness(physeq.prune.rarefy, x="Treatment", color=("Extraction"), measures=c("Observed")) + geom_boxplot(lwd=0.5) + ggtitle("Alpha Diversity by Treatment") + stat_compare_means(method = "t.test", label.x.npc = c("right")) + theme_bw() + scale_colour_brewer(palette="Set1") + theme(panel.grid.major = element_blank(), panel.grid.minor = element_blank())
